{"title_page": "Oliverio Rinc\u00f3n", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Rinc\u00f3n|Quintana}} \n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Mohammad amin\n| image         =\n| full_name     = Oliverio Rinc\u00f3n Quintana\n| nickname      = amin\n| birth_date    = 10/07/1998\n age|1968|04|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[kota]], [[Boyac\u00e1 Department|Boyac\u00e1]], Colombia\n| currentteam   = Retired\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = Climbing specialist\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     = 1990\n| proteam1      = [[Postob\u00f3n (cycling team)|Post\u00f3bon-Manzana]]\n| proyears2     = 1991&ndash;1992\n| proteam2      = {{ct|KEL|1991}}\n| proyears3     = 1993\n| proteam3      = Amaya-Razesa\n| proyears4     = 1994&ndash;1996\n| proteam4      = {{ct|ONC|1994}}\n| proyears5     = 1998\n| proteam5      = {{ct|VIT|1998}}\n| majorwins     = [[Tour de France]]\n:1 stage\n[[Giro d'Italia]]\n:1 stage\n[[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n:2 stages\n}}\n\n'''Oliverio Rinc\u00f3n Quintana''' (born April 24, 1968) is a [[Colombian people|Colombian]] former [[road bicycle racer]]. He is the older brother of [[Daniel Rinc\u00f3n]].\n\n==Major results==\n{{Div col}}\n;1989\n:1st, Overall, [[Vuelta a Colombia]]\n::1st, Stages 5 & 7\n;1991\n:1st, Overall, [[Escalada a Montju\u00efc]]\n::1st, Stages 1 & 2\n:1st, Stage 6, [[Vuelta a Burgos]]\n:10th, Overall, [[1991 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n;1993\n:2nd, Overall, [[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n::1st, Stage 6\n:1st, Stage 15, [[1993 Tour de France|Tour de France]]\n:1st, Stage 5, [[Vuelta a Arag\u00f3n]]\n:4th, Overall, [[1993 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n::1st, Stage 17\n;1994\n:1st, [[Classique des Alpes]]\n:5th, Overall, [[1994 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n;1995\n:5th, Overall, [[1995 Giro d'Italia|Giro d'Italia]]\n::1st, Stage 14\n;1996\n:1st, Stage 17, [[1996 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{CycleBase|13570|Oliverio RINCON QUINTANA}}\n*{{Cycling Archives|4474|Oliviero Rinc\u00f3n Quintana}}\n*[http://www.cyclingbase.com/palcoureurs.php?id=2522&idtitle=1 Palmares by cyclingbase.com]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rincon, Oliverio}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Colombian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombian Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:Colombian Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a stage winners]]\n[[Category:Colombian Giro d'Italia stage winners]]\n[[Category:People from Boyac\u00e1 Department]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{colombia-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Rinc\u00f3n|Quintana}} \n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Oliverio Rinc\u00f3n\n| image         =\n| full_name     = Oliverio Rinc\u00f3n Quintana\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1968|04|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[Duitama]], [[Boyac\u00e1 Department|Boyac\u00e1]], Colombia\n| currentteam   = Retired\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = Climbing specialist\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     = 1990\n| proteam1      = [[Postob\u00f3n (cycling team)|Post\u00f3bon-Manzana]]\n| proyears2     = 1991&ndash;1992\n| proteam2      = {{ct|KEL|1991}}\n| proyears3     = 1993\n| proteam3      = Amaya-Razesa\n| proyears4     = 1994&ndash;1996\n| proteam4      = {{ct|ONC|1994}}\n| proyears5     = 1998\n| proteam5      = {{ct|VIT|1998}}\n| majorwins     = [[Tour de France]]\n:1 stage\n[[Giro d'Italia]]\n:1 stage\n[[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]]\n:2 stages\n}}\n\n'''Oliverio Rinc\u00f3n Quintana''' (born April 24, 1968) is a [[Colombian people|Colombian]] former [[road bicycle racer]]. He is the older brother of [[Daniel Rinc\u00f3n]].\n\n==Major results==\n{{Div col}}\n;1989\n:1st, Overall, [[Vuelta a Colombia]]\n::1st, Stages 5 & 7\n;1991\n:1st, Overall, [[